A second reason was the arrival of television in 
the 1950s and 1960s as a new medium

4
00:00:24,866 --> 00:00:29,432
with even more power of attraction than its 
predecessors

5
00:00:29,433 --> 00:00:35,033
The effects of television were presumed huge, 
but not in the old 'magic bullet' way.

6
00:00:35,033 --> 00:00:38,399
Not so much direct, short term, and uniform, but

7
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:41,166
1) Long term, with repeated exposure.

8
00:00:41,166 --> 00:00:46,332
One new theory called cultivation proposed that 
after repeated long term exposure

9
00:00:46,333 --> 00:00:51,899
audiences tend to shift towards the dominant 
media viewpoints on matters.

10
00:00:51,900 --> 00:00:55,266
2) Indirect effects, much more attention was 
given now to

11
00:00:55,266 --> 00:00:58,266
indirect effects like associated effects.

12
00:00:58,266 --> 00:01:02,999
For instance, when we see a commercial of a 
muscular man eating ice cream we might not

13
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:09,933
run in to the shop to immediately buy ice cream. 
But perhaps after several commercials like this,

14
00:01:09,933 --> 00:01:15,266
we will associate this particular brand with a 
healthy appearance,

15
