40
00:02:56,266 --> 00:03:00,799
And you know, to some extent, this is true.

41
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:06,400
Television became a preferred way to spend 
time, alone or together.

42
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:09,300
Shows and series were a way to identify 
yourself, as an audience member

43
00:03:09,300 --> 00:03:13,500
or even as a fan of that particular program

44
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:19,200
Social Learning, when people learn skills or how 
to behave in situations in a social setting,

45
00:03:19,200 --> 00:03:21,166
proved to be quite effective through television. 

46
00:03:21,166 --> 00:03:26,666
Even though I have never been in a fire, I have 
some idea what to do and avoid, 

47
00:03:26,666 --> 00:03:32,932
because of many movies and series. If these 
ideas are correct of course, remains to be seen,

48
00:03:32,933 --> 00:03:36,199
but I do have some inkling based on media 
exposure.

49
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:42,200
Just like I think I know what to expect in a 
courtroom, space shuttle, or dinosaur attack. 

50
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:47,833
Not because of direct experience, but through 
mediated experience.

51
00:03:47,833 --> 00:03:52,066
Other scholars established Socialization Effects 
for television. 

52
00:03:52,066 --> 00:03:57,199
Socialization is when we learn norms and values 
in a informal way.

53
00:03:57,200 --> 00:04:02,666
Just like we learn from our parents, family, and 
friends, we learn from television as well.

54
00:04:02,666 --> 00:04:06,999
All of these effects were probably not unique for 
television compared to other media,

55
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:11,166
but they were very apparent in television.

56
00:04:11,166 --> 00:04:16,732
It was probably the rise of television more than 
anything that caused the final paradigm,

57
00:04:16,733 --> 00:04:20,366
a compromise between minimal and powerful 
effects.

58
00:04:20,366 --> 00:04:25,266
This is the dominant paradigm of today, that of 
negotiated media effects.

